===Etymology===
1784,<ref name="oetyld"/> from Hindustani ({{etyl|hi}}-{{etyl|ur}}) {{term|sc=Deva|अवतार|lang=hi}} / {{term|sc=ur-Arab|اوتار|tr=avatār|lang=ur}}, from {{etyl|sa}} {{term|sc=Deva|अवतार|tr=ava-tāra||descent of a deity from a heaven|lang=sa}}, a compound of {{term|sc=Deva|अव|tr=ava||off, away, down|lang=sa}} and the [[vṛddhi]]-stem of the root {{term|sc=unicode|तरति|√tṝ|to cross|lang=sa}}.

In computing use, saw some use in 1980s videos games – 1985 online role-playing game ''[[w:Habitat (video game)|Habitat]]'' by Lucasfilm Games (today {{w|LucasArts}}), by {{w|Chip Morningstar}} and {{w|Joseph Romero}},<ref name="Morabito">Morabito, Margaret. "Enter the Online World of LucasFilm." Run Aug. 1986: 24-28</ref> later versions of the ''[[w:Ultima (video game series)|Ultima]]'' series (following religious use in 1985 ''{{w|Ultima IV: Quest of the Avatar}}''), and 1989 {{w|pen and paper}} role-playing game ''{{w|Shadowrun}}.'' Popularized by 1992 novel ''{{w|Snow Crash}}'' by {{w|Neal Stephenson}}.<ref name="oetyld">{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

